{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656574"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:15:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:15:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18748"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18748"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11480"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78455"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11480"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18748"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63817"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10473"},{"type":"tags","id":"11225"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26574"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26580"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78455"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMuscle spindles are specialised sensory receptors found in skeletal muscle that contribute to proprioception and motor control.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the response properties of muscle spindle primary (type Ia) afferents?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Respond only to rapid stretch","Detect muscle tension exclusively","Respond to both rate and magnitude of stretch","Signal only static muscle length","Signal muscle contraction force"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eresponse to both rate and magnitude of stretch\u003C/strong\u003E is the key characteristic of primary (type Ia) muscle spindle afferents. These sensory endings wrap around the central region of intrafusal muscle fibres and are sensitive to both dynamic (velocity) and static (length) components of muscle stretch.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESignal only static muscle length\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes type II (secondary) afferents, not type Ia afferents\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetect muscle tension exclusively\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of Golgi tendon organs, not muscle spindles\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERespond only to rapid stretch\u003C/strong\u003E - While type Ia afferents are sensitive to velocity, they also respond to maintained stretch\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESignal muscle contraction force\u003C/strong\u003E - Force detection is primarily handled by Golgi tendon organs, not muscle spindles\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe dual sensitivity of type Ia afferents to both dynamic and static components makes them crucial for detecting sudden perturbations in muscle length and maintaining proper muscle tone and posture.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Muscle spindles detect changes in muscle length and stretch velocity through primary and secondary sensory endings.","Primary (type Ia) afferents respond to both the rate and magnitude of muscle stretch.","Secondary (type II) afferents primarily signal static muscle length."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemR